[[File:Salami sandwich.jpg|thumb|right|A salami [[sandwich]]]] '''Make me a sandwich''' is a [[catchphrase]] used in [[popular culture]], often on the internet, to mock or discredit women in a satirical manner. It is a stereotype based on women belonging in the kitchen.<ref name="noton">(19 April 2010). [http://www.statecollege.com/news/columns/make-me-a-sandwich-not-on-my-watch-391391/ Make Me a Sandwich? Not on My Watch], StateCollege.com</ref><ref name="couric">Elsworth, Catherine (25 July 2008). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3560961/Katie-Couric-is-right-to-criticise-sexist-US.html Katie Couric is right to criticise sexist US], ''The Telegraph''</ref>
For example, during [[Hillary Clinton]]'s 2008 campaign for the Democratic nomination for United States President, it was noted in the news that a [[Facebook]] group had been created titled "Hillary Clinton: Stop Running for President and Make Me a Sandwich."<ref name="abc">Shipman, Claire (30 May 2008). [http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Vote2008/story?id=4964491&page=1#.UXqEjErd7To Hey Hill: Love Your Hair, Now Iron My Shirt], ''[[ABC News]]''</ref><ref name="fem1">Fortini, Amanda (13 April 2008). [http://nymag.com/news/features/46011/ The Feminist Reawakening], ''New York Magazine''</ref>
The phrase, as used in an intended humorous context, dates to at least 1995.<ref name="gendder1">Johnson, Allan (10 September 1995). [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/21339589.html?dids=21339589:21339589&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+10%2C+1995&author=Allan+Johnson%2C+Tribune+Staff+Writer.&pub=Chicago+Tribune+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=NO+GENDER+IS+OFF+LIMITS+FOR+SCHMIDT&pqatl=google No Gender Is Off Limits for Schmidt], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''</ref>
